  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane households have at least one pet, and most sellers with pets successfully sell their homes every week without incident. The challenges are real but manageable, and they all have practical solutions. The goal is not to hide the fact that animals live in your home. It's to present the property so that buyers focus on its potential rather than on the presence of your animals. That distinction matters, because buyers who feel a property has been prepared honestly and thoroughly tend to have higher confidence in the purchase than those who sense something is being concealed.</p>

      <p>The issues that actually matter to buyers fall into three categories: smell, visible damage, and the logistics of open homes. Each of these is addressable, and addressing them properly before you list will protect your campaign from the kinds of buyer objections that lead to discounting or missed sales.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Odour is the issue sellers underestimate most</h2>
      <p>Pet owners typically stop noticing the smell of their animals. Buyers notice it immediately, and it registers as one of the first and most lasting impressions they form of a property. This is not about judgment, it's just how familiarity with a smell works. A buyer who walks into a home and is greeted by a strong animal smell will mentally flag the property as a problem before they have even looked at the kitchen or the backyard. That initial impression is difficult to recover from during the rest of the inspection.</p>

      <p>The most effective approach to pet odour starts several weeks before your first open home. Begin by having all soft furnishings cleaned, including carpets, curtains, and upholstered furniture. Professional carpet steam cleaning from a company experienced with pet odour, rather than a standard clean, makes a material difference. Hard floors should be mopped with an enzyme-based cleaner rather than a standard floor product, as enzyme cleaners break down odour at the source rather than masking it.</p>

      <p>Washing pet bedding, removing it from the property during inspections, and cleaning any areas where animals sleep or spend significant time (including underneath furniture and in corners) addresses the primary sources. For properties with indoor cats, particular attention to litter tray locations and surrounding areas is important. Good ventilation in the days before and on the day of an open home also helps significantly. If you are uncertain whether there is residual odour after your cleaning efforts, ask someone who has not been in the home recently to give you an honest assessment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Visible damage: what to fix and what to leave</h2>
      <p>Pet-related damage varies from minor marks that buyers will barely notice to significant issues that will affect their willingness to proceed or the price they offer. The judgment call is about return on investment: some repairs are straightforward and cheap relative to the impression they create, while others cost more to fix than the value they add.</p>

      <p>Scratched timber floors are a common issue with dogs and indoor cats. Depending on the severity and the floor type, a professional sand and polish can restore the floor to a condition that reads as high quality on photography and in person. If the floor is beyond economical repair, it may be worth replacing. Your selling agent can advise based on comparable sales whether buyers in your price range expect polished timber or whether the cost of replacement is recoverable in the price. Scratched door frames and skirting boards are generally cheap to repair and repaint, and worth doing.</p>

      <p>Yard damage from dogs, including worn paths along fence lines and patches in lawn areas, can often be addressed with turf repair and some attention to garden presentation. The principle is that the yard should look actively maintained rather than neglected. A buyer who sees a worn path along a fence understands a dog lives there. A buyer who sees a worn path in an otherwise tidy, well-presented yard will process it differently than one who sees it in an unkempt space where everything looks tired.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing open homes and private inspections</h2>
      <p>Pets should not be present during open homes or private inspections. This is a non-negotiable point. A dog that barks, jumps at buyers, or needs to be restrained distracts from the property and makes some buyers uncomfortable or even anxious. A cat that wanders through inspections is less disruptive but still pulls attention. Buyers should be focused on the property, not on managing interactions with your animals.</p>

      <p>Organise for your pets to be taken off the property for every inspection from the beginning of the campaign. For open homes, this means a car trip, a visit to a friend or family member, or time at a pet day care facility. For private inspections, which can be requested on short notice, having a plan in place before the campaign begins avoids the scramble of finding somewhere for a dog to go on 30 minutes' notice during a busy week.</p>

      <p>All pet-related items should also be removed or stored out of sight during inspections. Bowls, toys, kennels, cat trees, litter trays, and leads sitting on benches or in living areas all reinforce the presence of animals in a way that serves no purpose for buyers. Storing this equipment tidily in a shed or garage is easy and makes a noticeable difference to how the internal spaces read during an inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Photography and the campaign</h2>
      <p>The photography and video for your campaign should be completed with all pet items removed and the property in its best presentation state. This includes the backyard, where a dog kennel or outdoor pet enclosure in a hero shot of the outdoor entertaining area will anchor buyer attention on the wrong thing. The photography should show the property at its best, and buyers who have pets themselves will understand that pets were present regardless of whether the evidence is visible in the images.</p>

      <p>There is no need to disclose the presence of pets in your marketing copy. You are required to disclose material facts about the property under Queensland law, and the presence of pets in a home is not a material fact unless there is damage that has not been remediated. The job of good marketing is to show the property honestly and attractively. Clean, well-lit, pet-free photography achieves that.</p>

